It made me think how much we ourselves actually contribute to creating prejudices in our children.
Because I will tell you that, in reality, according to my way of seeing, work is not a place where you go.
Work is changing, it is changing profoundly.
I'm going to tell you some things that support my thesis.
It is changing because there are increasingly rare skills, but increasingly required by the market and companies.
A BCG study has certified that about 30 percent of high-tech positions will be vacant in the next 18 to 24 months due to lack of skills.
You imagine: 30 percent of the positions will remain unfilled due to lack of skills, especially in the world of data science and machine learning, so the most modern, most advanced skills.
So, from this point of view, we are a bit of a struggle to build the skills that we want to see in our organizations of the future.
We chase them.
Another interesting fact is that about 66 percent of CIOs, the managers of companies' IT infrastructures, say that the scarcity of talent is approaching crisis dimensions, so it is becoming a very strong theme.
Another very important element: artificial intelligence and automation and robotization are changing the world of work.
The same BCG study, which I invite you to read, is called: "12 forces that are changing the way organizations work" has certified that, within the next 10 years, 70 percent of the professions we do today will have changed drastically or even disappear.
And, if we look at what the World Economic Forum says, two-thirds of children studying in primary school today are preparing for jobs that do not yet exist.
Impressive, if I think of my children who now attend elementary school.
Another theme: the average life of some skills, of some engineering skills, has dropped drastically and today it is between two and a half and five years.
What does that mean?
That if a person does not put himself in mind to invest in himself and to play the game of continuous learning will be, in a short time, not very "employable", not very employable.
But there are also some softer forces that are changing the world of work.
For example, having a strong culture within the organization.
The fact that about 90 percent of companies consider culture a distinctive and competitive factor for the success of the organization is certainly something very significant, very important.
And, from this point of view, there is correspondence.
Because even the people who live in organizations are putting culture and a sense of purpose at the center of their journey.
62 percent of millennials don't want a job, they don't want a salary, they don't want an office job.
He wants to have a career that has a strong social impact.
And, this is my opinion, it is probably not only millennials who want a job, a career that helps them to have a strong social impact.
Another soft force that is changing the world of work is the increasing attention to the world, the theme of diversity and inclusion.
In the United States, 80 percent of people employed in organizations say that it is a factor in choosing their position and the company that organizations put diversity at the center.
